# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: argument-linguistics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] In linguistics, an **adjunct** is an optional, or *structurally dispensable*, part of a sentence, clause, or phrase that, if removed or discarded, will not structurally affect the remainder of the sentence.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Example: In the sentence *John helped Bill in Central Park*, the phrase *in Central Park* is an adjunct.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] A more detailed definition of the adjunct emphasizes its attribute as a modifying form, word, or phrase that depends on another form, word, or phrase, being an element of clause structure with adverbial function.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] An adjunct is not an argument (nor is it a predicative expression), and an argument is not an adjunct.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The argument–adjunct distinction is central in most theories of syntax and semantics.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The terminology used to denote arguments and adjuncts can vary depending on the theory at hand.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Some dependency grammars, for instance, employ the term *circonstant* (instead of *adjunct*), following Tesnière (1959).
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The area of grammar that explores the nature of predicates, their arguments, and adjuncts is called valency theory.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Predicates have valency; they determine the number and type of arguments that can or must appear in their environment.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The valency of predicates is also investigated in terms of subcategorization.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] An *adverbial adjunct* is a sentence element that often establishes the circumstances in which the action or state expressed by the verb takes place.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Notice that this example is ambiguous between whether the adjunct *in the garden* modifies the verb *saw* (in which case it is Lorna who saw the dog while she was in the garden) or the noun phrase *the dog* (in which case it is the dog who is in the garden).
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The definition can be extended to include adjuncts that modify nouns or other parts of speech (see noun adjunct).
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] An adjunct can be a single word, a phrase, or an entire clause.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Most discussions of adjuncts focus on adverbial adjuncts, that is, on adjuncts that modify verbs, verb phrases, or entire clauses like the adjuncts in the three examples just given.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Adjuncts can appear in other domains, however; that is, they can modify most categories.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] An **adnominal** adjunct is one that modifies a noun: for a list of possible types of these, see Components of noun phrases.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Adjuncts that modify adjectives and adverbs are occasionally called *adadjectival* and *adadverbial*.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Each of the adjuncts in the examples throughout this article is a constituent.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Adjuncts can be categorized in terms of the functional meaning that they contribute to the phrase, clause, or sentence in which they appear.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] – Causal adjuncts establish the reason for, or purpose of, an action or state.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] – Concessive adjuncts establish contrary circumstances.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] – Conditional adjuncts establish the condition in which an action occurs or state holds.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] – Consecutive adjuncts establish an effect or result.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] – Final adjuncts establish the goal of an action (what one wants to accomplish).
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] – Instrumental adjuncts establish the instrument used to accomplish an action.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] – Locative adjuncts establish where, to where, or from where a state or action happened or existed.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] – Modal adjuncts establish the extent to which the speaker views the action or state as (im)probable.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] – Modificative adjuncts establish how the action happened or the state existed.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] – Temporal adjuncts establish when, how long, or how frequent the action or state happened or existed.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The distinction between arguments and adjuncts and predicates is central to most theories of syntax and grammar.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Predicates take arguments and they permit (certain) adjuncts.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The arguments of a predicate are necessary to complete the meaning of the predicate.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The adjuncts of a predicate, in contrast, provide auxiliary information about the core predicate-argument meaning, which means they are not necessary to complete the meaning of the predicate.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Adjuncts and arguments can be identified using various diagnostics.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The omission diagnostic, for instance, helps identify many arguments and thus many possible adjuncts as well.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] If a given constituent cannot be omitted from a sentence, clause, or phrase without resulting in an unacceptable expression, that constituent is *not* an adjunct.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] In contrast, if a given constituent can be omitted without affecting grammaticality or core meaning, that constituent *is* an adjunct.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] I know. - the sentence is acceptable, but its meaning is changed entirely.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Further diagnostics used to distinguish between arguments and adjuncts include multiplicity, distance from head, and the ability to coordinate.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] is a noun phrase that functions as object argument.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The distinction between arguments and adjuncts is much less clear than the simple omission diagnostic (and the other diagnostics) suggests.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Most accounts of the argument vs. adjunct distinction acknowledge a further division.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] One distinguishes between obligatory and optional arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Optional arguments pattern like adjuncts when just the omission diagnostic is employed, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] is not an obligatory argument, but it could be (and it is) an optional argument.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The existence of optional arguments blurs the line between arguments and adjuncts considerably.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Further diagnostics (beyond the omission diagnostic and the others mentioned above) must be employed to distinguish between adjuncts and optional arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] One such diagnostic is the relative clause test.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The test constituent is moved from the matrix clause to a subordinate relative clause containing *which occurred/happened*.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] is not an adjunct, which means it must be an optional argument.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The particular merit of the relative clause test is its ability to distinguish between many argument and adjunct PPs, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The reliability of the relative clause diagnostic is actually limited.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] For instance, it incorrectly suggests that many modal and manner adjuncts are arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] This fact bears witness to the difficulty of providing an absolute diagnostic for the distinctions currently being examined.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Despite the difficulties, most theories of syntax and grammar distinguish on the one hand between arguments and adjuncts and on the other hand between optional arguments and adjuncts, and they grant a central position to these divisions in the overarching theory.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Many phrases have the outward appearance of an adjunct but are in fact (part of) a predicate instead.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The confusion occurs often with copular verbs, in particular with a form of *be*, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The PPs in these sentences are neither adjuncts nor arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The preposition in each case is, rather, part of the main predicate.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The matrix predicate in the first sentence is *is under*; this predicate takes the two arguments *It* and *the bush*.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Similarly, the matrix predicate in the second sentence is *is at*; this predicate takes the two arguments *The party* and *seven o'clock*.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Distinguishing between predicates, arguments, and adjuncts becomes particularly difficult when secondary predicates are involved, for instance with resultative predicates, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The resultative adjective *tired* can be viewed as an argument of the matrix predicate *made*.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] But it is also definitely a predicate over *him*.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Such examples illustrate that distinguishing predicates, arguments, and adjuncts can become difficult and there are many cases where a given expression functions in more ways than one.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] This overview acknowledges three types of entities: predicates, arguments, and adjuncts, whereby arguments are further divided into obligatory and optional ones.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Many theories of syntax and grammar employ trees to represent the structure of sentences.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Various conventions are used to distinguish between arguments and adjuncts in these trees.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] In phrase structure grammars, many adjuncts are distinguished from arguments insofar as the adjuncts of a head predicate will appear higher in the structure than the object argument(s) of that predicate.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The adjunct is adjoined to a projection of the head predicate above and to the right of the object argument, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The object argument each time is identified insofar as it is a sister of V that appears to the right of V, and the adjunct status of the adverb *early* and the PP *before class* is seen in the higher position to the right of and above the object argument.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Other adjuncts, in contrast, are assumed to adjoin to a position that is between the subject argument and the head predicate or above and to the left of the subject argument, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The subject is identified as an argument insofar as it appears as a sister and to the left of V(P).
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The modal adverb *certainly* is shown as an adjunct insofar as it adjoins to an intermediate projection of V or to a projection of S.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] In X-bar theory, adjuncts are represented as elements that are sisters to X' levels and daughters of X' level [X' adjunct [X'...]].
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Theories that assume sentence structure to be less layered than the analyses just given sometimes employ a special convention to distinguish adjuncts from arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] Some dependency grammars, for instance, use an arrow dependency edge to mark adjuncts, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The arrow dependency edge points away from the adjunct toward the governor of the adjunct.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The arrows identify six adjuncts: *Yesterday*, *probably*, *many times*, *very*, *very long*, and *that you like*.
[src:argument-linguistics/adjunct-grammar] The standard, non-arrow dependency edges identify *Sam*, *Susan*, *that very long story that you like*, etc. as arguments (of one of the predicates in the sentence).
[src:argument-linguistics/affect-linguistics] In linguistics, **affect** is an attitude or emotion that a speaker brings to an utterance.
[src:argument-linguistics/affect-linguistics] Lexical choices may frame a speaker's affect, such as *slender* (positive affect) vs.
[src:argument-linguistics/affect-linguistics] *scrawny* (negative affect), *thrifty* (positive) vs.
[src:argument-linguistics/affect-linguistics] *stingy* (negative) and *freedom fighter* (positive) vs.
[src:argument-linguistics/affect-linguistics] In many languages of Europe, augmentative derivations are used to express contempt or other negative attitudes toward the noun being so modified, whereas diminutives may express affection; on the other hand, diminutives are frequently used to belittle or be dismissive.
[src:argument-linguistics/affect-linguistics] For instance, in Spanish, a name ending in diminutive *-ito* (masculine) or *-ita* (feminine) may be a term of endearment, but *señorito* "little mister" for *señor* "mister" may be mocking.
[src:argument-linguistics/affect-linguistics] Polish has a range of augmentative and diminutive forms, which express differences in affect.
[src:argument-linguistics/affect-linguistics] So, from *żaba* "a frog", besides *żabucha* for simply a big frog, there is augmentative *żabsko* to express distaste, *żabisko* if the frog is ugly, *żabula* if it is likeably awkward, etc.
[src:argument-linguistics/affect-linguistics] Affect can also be conveyed by more subtle means.
[src:argument-linguistics/affect-linguistics] Duranti, for example, shows that the use of pronouns in Italian narration indicates that the character referred to is important to the narration but is generally also a mark of a positive speaker attitude toward the character.
[src:argument-linguistics/affect-linguistics] In Japanese and Korean, grammatical affect is conveyed both through honorific, polite, and humble language, which affects both nouns and verbal inflection, and through clause-final particles that express a range of speaker emotions and attitudes toward what is being said.
[src:argument-linguistics/affect-linguistics] ʔaː=tʼo béda=ht̪ow béː=yo-w dá-ːʔ-du-w tʃʰó-w. béda ʔaː qʼlá-w=ʔkʰe.
[src:argument-linguistics/affect-linguistics] "(But) I don't want to go away from here.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] In linguistics and grammar, **affirmation** (abbreviated **aff**) and **negation** (**neg**) are ways in which grammar encodes positive and negative polarity into verb phrases, clauses, or utterances.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] An affirmative (positive) form is used to express the validity or truth of a basic assertion, while a negative form expresses its falsity.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] For example, the affirmative sentence "Joe is here" asserts that it is true that Joe is currently located near the speaker.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Conversely, the negative sentence "Joe is not here" asserts that it is not true that Joe is currently located near the speaker.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] The grammatical category associated with affirmatives and negatives is called **polarity**.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] This means that a clause, sentence, verb phrase, etc. may be said to have either affirmative or negative polarity (its polarity may be either affirmative or negative).
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Affirmative is typically the unmarked polarity, whereas a negative statement is marked in some way.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Negative polarity can be indicated by negating words or particles such as the English *not*, or the Japanese affix -ない -*nai*, or by other means, which reverses the meaning of the predicate.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] The process of converting affirmative to negative is called **negation** – the grammatical rules for negation vary from language to language, and a given language may have multiple methods of negation.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Affirmative and negative responses (specifically, though not exclusively, to questions) are often expressed using particles or words such as *yes* and *no*, where *yes* is the affirmative, or positive particle, and *no* is the negation, or negative particle.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Affirmation and negation are crucial building blocks for language.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] The presence of negation is the absence of affirmation, where affirmation functions individually.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] There are three main aspects to the concept of affirmation and negation; Cognitive, psychological and philosophical (Schopenhauer's theory or Nietzschean affirmation).
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Negation in English is more difficult for the brain to process as it works in opposition to affirmation.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] If affirmation and negation were missing from language people would only be able to communicate through possibilities.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] The recent Reusing Inhibition for Negation (RIN) hypothesis states that there is a specific inhibitory control mechanism (one that is reused) that is needed when trying to understand negation in sentences.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Affirmations or positive polarity items (PPIs) are expressions that are rejected by negation, usually escaping the scope of negation.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] PPIs in the literature have been associated with speaker-oriented adverbs, as well as expressions similar to *some*, *already*, and *would rather*.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Affirmative sentences work in opposition to negations.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] The affirmative, in an English example such as "the police chief here is a woman", declares a simple fact; in this case, a fact regarding the police chief, asserting that she is a woman.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] In contrast, the negative, in an English example such as "the police chief here is not a man", is stated as an assumption for people to believe.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] It is also widely believed that the affirmative is the unmarked base form from which the negative is produced, but this can be argued when coming from a pragmatic standpoint.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Pragmatically, affirmatives can sometimes derive the pragmatically unmarked form, or, at times, create novel affirmative derivatives.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Affirmation can also be compared to the notion of assertiveness.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Affirmation can be indicated with the following words in English: *some,* *certainly*, *already,* and *would rather.* Two examples of affirmation include (1) John is here already and (2) I am a moral person.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] These two sentences are truth statements, and serve as a representation of affirmation in English.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] The negated versions can be formed as the statements (1NEG) John is not here already and (2NEG) I am not a moral person.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] In Dagaare, there are verbal suffixes, such as *-ng*, that serve as an affirmation or an emphasis to a verbal action.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] There are also cases of the identifying pronoun *na* developing into an affirmative marker.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] *na* is reanalyzed into a clause final particle simultaneously with the denominalisation of the clausal subject which brings the result of *na* as a clause nominalising particle which can again be reanalyzed as a positive, future, marker.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] This clause final particle is known to only be used to mark assertiveness in positive clauses because it is not seen co-occurring with negative markers.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Simple grammatical negation of a clause, in principle, has the effect of converting a proposition to its logical negation.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] This is done by replacing an assertion that something is the case with an assertion that it is not the case.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] In some cases, however, particularly when a particular modality is expressed, the semantic effect of negation may be somewhat different.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] For example, in English, the meaning of "you must not go" is not the exact negation of "you must go".
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] The exact negation of this phrase would be expressed as "you don't have to go" or "you needn't go".
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] The negation "must not" has a stronger meaning (the effect is to apply the logical negation to the following infinitive rather than applying it to the full clause with *must*).
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] For more details and other similar cases, see the relevant sections of English modal verbs.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Negation flips downward entailing and upward entailing statements within the scope of the negation.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] For example, changing "one could have seen anything" to "no one could have seen anything" changes the meaning of the last word from "anything" to "nothing".
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] In some cases, by way of irony, an affirmative statement may be intended to have the meaning of the corresponding negative, or vice versa.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] For examples see antiphrasis and sarcasm.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] For the use of double negations or similar as understatements ("not unappealing", "not bad", etc.) see litotes.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Languages have a variety of grammatical rules for converting affirmative verb phrases or clauses into negative ones.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] In many languages, an affirmative is made negative by the addition of a particle, meaning "not".
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Other examples of negating particles preceding the verb phrase include Italian *non*, Russian не *nye* and Polish *nie*; they can also be found in constructed languages: *ne* in Esperanto and *non* in Interlingua.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Particles following the verb in this way include *not* in archaic and dialectal English ("you remember not"), *nicht* in German (*ich schlafe nicht*, "I am not sleeping"), and *inte* in Swedish (*han hoppade inte*, "he did not jump").
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] However, in colloquial French the first particle is often omitted: *Je sais pas*.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Similar use of two negating particles can also be found in Afrikaans: *Hy kan **nie** Afrikaans praat **nie*** ("He cannot speak Afrikaans").
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] In English, negation is achieved by adding *not* after the verb.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] As a practical matter, Modern English typically uses a copula verb (a form of *be*) or an auxiliary verb with *not*.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] If no other auxiliary verb is present, then dummy auxiliary *do* (*does*, *did*) is normally introduced – see *do*-support.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] but that wording is considered archaic and is rarely used.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] (since there is no auxiliary in the original sentence).
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Different rules apply in subjunctive, imperative and non-finite clauses.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] For more details see English grammar § Negation.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] (In Middle English, the particle *not* could follow any verb, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] In some languages, like Welsh, verbs have special inflections to be used in negative clauses.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] (In some language families, this may lead to reference to a negative mood.) An example is Japanese, which conjugates verbs in the negative after adding the suffix -ない -*nai* (indicating negation); e.g., 食べる *taberu* ("eat") and 食べない *tabe**nai*** ("do not eat").
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] It could be argued that English has joined the ranks of these languages, since negation requires the use of an auxiliary verb and a distinct syntax in most cases; the form of the basic verb can change on negation, as in "he **sings**" vs.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Zwicky and Pullum have shown that *n't* is an inflectional suffix, not a clitic or a derivational suffix.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Complex rules for negation also apply in Finnish; see Finnish grammar § Negation of verbs.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] In some languages negation may also affect the dependents of the verb; for example in some Slavic languages, such as Polish, the case of a direct object often changes from accusative to genitive when the verb is negated.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Negation can be applied not just to whole verb phrases, clauses or sentences, but also to specific elements (such as adjectives and noun phrases) within sentences.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] This contrast is usually labeled *sentential negation* versus *constituent negation*.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Ways in which this constituent negation is realized depends on the grammar of the language in question.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] English generally places *not* before the negated element, as in "I witnessed **not a debate**, but a war." There are also negating affixes, such as the English prefixes *non-*, *un-*, *in-*, etc.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] There also exist elements which carry a specialized negative meaning, including pronouns such as *nobody*, *none* and *nothing*, determiners such as *no* (as in "no apples"), and adverbs such as *never*, *no longer* and *nowhere*.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Although such elements themselves have negative force, in some languages a clause in which they appear is additionally marked for ordinary negation.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] For example, in Russian, "I see nobody" is expressed as я никого не вижу *ja nikovo nye vizhu*, literally "I nobody not see" – the ordinary negating particle не *nye* ("not") is used in addition to the negative pronoun никого *nikovo* ("nobody").
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Italian behaves in a similar way: *Non ti vede nessuno* ("nobody can see you"), although *Nessuno ti vede* is also a possible clause with exactly the same meaning.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] In Russian, all of the elements ("not", "never", "nobody", "nowhere") appear together in the sentence in their negative form.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] In Italian, a clause works much as in Russian, but *non* does not have to be there, and can be there only before the verb if it precedes all other negative elements: *Tu non porti mai nessuno da nessuna parte*.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] "Nobody ever brings you anything here", however, could be translated *Nessuno qui ti porta mai niente* or *Qui non ti porta mai niente nessuno*.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] In Dagaare, negation is marked specifically by pre-verb particles, where only four, out of the nearly 24 pre-verb particles, are designated as negation markers.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] The four negation markers are *ba*, *kʊ̀ŋ*, *ta*, and *tɔ́ɔ́*.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] To signal negation, as well as other semantic relation, these negation particles combine with different aspects of the verb.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] These pre-verb negatory particles can also be used to convey tense, mood, aspect, and polarity (negation), and in some cases can be used to convey more than one of these features.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Various signed and manual languages are known to negate via headshake.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Special affirmative and negative words (particles) are often found in responses to questions, and sometimes to other assertions by way of agreement or disagreement.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] In English, these are *yes* and *no* respectively; in French, *oui*, *si*, and *non*; in Danish *ja*, *jo* and *nej*; in Spanish, *sí* and *no*; and so on.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Not all languages make such common use of particles of this type; in some, such as Welsh, it is more common to repeat the verb or another part of the predicate, with or without negation accordingly.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Complications sometimes arise in the case of responses to negative statements or questions; in some cases the response that confirms a negative statement is the negative particle (as in English: "You're not going out?
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] No."), but in some languages this is reversed.
[src:argument-linguistics/affirmation-and-negation] Some languages have a distinct form to answer a negative question, such as French *si* and Danish *jo* (these serve to contradict the negative statement suggested by the first speaker).
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] In linguistics, a **grammatical agent** is the thematic relation of the cause or initiator to an event.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] The agent is a semantic concept distinct from the subject of a sentence as well as from the topic.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] While the subject is determined syntactically, primarily through word order, the agent is determined through its relationship to the action expressed by the verb.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] For example, in the sentence "The little girl was bitten by the dog", *girl* is the subject, but *dog* is the agent.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] The word *agent* comes from the present participle *agens*, *agentis* ('the one doing') of the Latin verb *agere*, to 'do' or 'make'.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] Typically, the situation is denoted by a sentence, the action by a verb in the sentence, and the agent by a noun phrase.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] For example, in the sentence "Jack kicked the ball", *Jack* is the agent and *the ball* is the patient.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] In certain languages, the agent is declined or otherwise marked to indicate its grammatical role.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] Modern English does not mark the agentive grammatical role of a noun in a sentence.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] Although certain nouns do have a permanent trait of agency (runner, kicker, etc.), an agent noun is not necessarily an agent of a sentence: "Jack kicked the runner".
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] For many people, the notion of agency is easy to grasp intuitively but difficult to define: typical qualities that a grammatical agent often has are that it has volition, is sentient or perceives, causes a change of state, or moves.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] The linguist David Dowty included these qualities in his definition of a Proto-Agent, and proposed that the nominal with the most elements of the Proto-Agent and the fewest elements of the Proto-Patient tends to be treated as the agent in a sentence.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] This solves problems that most semanticists have with deciding on the number and quality of thematic roles.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] For example, in the sentence *His energy surprised everyone*, *His energy* is the agent, even though it does not have most of the typical agent-like qualities such as perception, movement, or volition.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] (1) April precedes May. vs: (2) May follows April.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] Here what is agent and what is patient must be specified for each individual verb.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] The grammatical agent is often confused with the subject, but the two notions are quite distinct: the *agent* is based explicitly on its relationship to the action or event expressed by the verb (e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] "He who kicked the ball"), whereas the *subject* is based on a more *formal title* using the theory of the information flow (e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] In the sentence "The boy kicked the ball", *the boy* is the agent *and* the subject.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] However, when the sentence is rendered in the passive voice, "The ball was kicked by the boy", *the ball* is the grammatical subject, but *the boy* is still the agent.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] Many sentences in English and other Indo-European languages have the agent as subject.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] The use of some transitive verbs denoting strictly reciprocal events may involve a conflation of agent and subject.
[src:argument-linguistics/agent-grammar] In the sentence "John met Sylvia", for example, though both *John* and *Sylvia* would equally meet Dowty's definition of a Proto-Agent, the co-agent *Sylvia* is downgraded to patient because it is the direct object of the sentence.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In linguistics, **agreement** or **concord** (abbreviated **agr**) occurs when a word changes form depending on the other words to which it relates.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] It is an instance of inflection, and usually involves making the value of some grammatical category (such as gender or person) "agree" between varied words or parts of the sentence.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] For example, in Standard English, one may say *I am* or *he is*, but not "I is" or "he am".
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] This is because English grammar requires that the verb and its subject agree in *person*.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The pronouns *I* and *he* are first and third person respectively, as are the verb forms *am* and *is*.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The verb form must be selected so that it has the same person as the subject in contrast to notional agreement, which is based on meaning.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Agreement generally involves matching the value of some grammatical category between different constituents of a sentence (or sometimes between sentences, as in some cases where a pronoun is required to agree with its antecedent or referent).
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Some categories that commonly trigger grammatical agreement are noted below.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Agreement based on grammatical person is found mostly between verb and subject.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] *he is*) has been given in the introduction to this article.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Agreement between pronoun (or corresponding possessive adjective) and antecedent also requires the selection of the correct person.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] For example, if the antecedent is the first person noun phrase *Mary and I*, then a first person pronoun (*we/us/our*) is required; however, most noun phrases (*the dog*, *my cats*, *Jack and Jill*, etc.) are third person, and are replaced by a third person pronoun (*he/she/it/they* etc.).
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Agreement based on grammatical number can occur between verb and subject, as in the case of grammatical person discussed above.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In fact the two categories are often conflated within verb conjugation patterns: there are specific verb forms for first person singular, second person plural and so on.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Agreement also occurs between nouns and their specifier and modifiers, in some situations.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In languages in which grammatical gender plays a significant role, there is often agreement in gender between a noun and its modifiers.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Such agreement is also found with predicate adjectives: *l'homme est grand* ('the man is big') vs.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] *la chaise est grande* ('the chair is big').
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In the case of verbs, gender agreement is less common, although it may still occur, for example in Arabic verbs where the second and third persons take different inflections for masculine and feminine subjects.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In the French compound past tense, the past participle – formally an adjective – agrees in certain circumstances with the subject or with an object (see *passé composé* for details).
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Russian and most other Slavic languages, the form of the past tense agrees in gender with the subject, again due to derivation from an earlier adjectival construction.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] There is also agreement in gender between pronouns and their antecedents.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In languages that have a system of cases, there is often agreement by case between a noun and its modifiers.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In fact, the modifiers of nouns in languages such as German and Latin agree with their nouns in number, gender and case; all three categories are conflated together in paradigms of declension.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Case agreement is not a significant feature of English (only personal pronouns and the pronoun *who* have any case marking).
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] A rare type of agreement that phonologically copies parts of the head rather than agreeing with a grammatical category.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In this example, what is copied is not a prefix, but rather the initial syllable of the head 'river'.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Languages can have no conventional agreement whatsoever, as in Japanese or Malay; barely any, as in English; a small amount, as in spoken French; a moderate amount, as in Greek or Latin; or a large amount, as in Swahili.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Modern English does not have a particularly large amount of agreement, although it is present.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] All regular verbs (and nearly all irregular ones) in English agree in the third-person singular of the present indicative by adding a suffix of either *-s* or *-es*.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The latter is generally used after stems ending in the sibilants *sh*, *ch*, *ss,* or *zz* (e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] There is a distinction between irregular verb conjugations in the spoken language and irregular spellings of words in the written language.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Linguistics generally concerns itself with the natural, spoken language, and not with spelling conventions in the written language.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The verb *to go* is often given as an example of a verb with an irregular present tense conjugation, on account of adding "-es" instead of just "-s" for the third person singular conjugation.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] However, this is merely an arbitrary spelling convention.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In the spoken language, the present tense conjugation of *to go* is entirely regular.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] If we were to classify *to go* as irregular based on the spelling of *goes*, then by the same reasoning, we would have to include other regular verbs with irregular spelling conventions such as *to veto/vetoes*, *to echo/echoes*, *to carry/carries*, *to hurry/hurries*, etc.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In contrast, the verb *to do* is actually irregular in its spoken third-person singular conjugation, in addition to having a somewhat irregular spelling.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] While the verb *do* rhymes with *shoe*, its conjugation *does* does not rhyme with *shoes*; the verb *does* rhymes with *fuzz*.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Conversely, the verb *to say*, while it may appear to be regular based on its spelling, is in fact irregular in its third person singular present tense conjugation: *Say* is pronounced /seɪ/, but *says* is pronounced /sɛz/.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] *Say* rhymes with *pay*, but *says* does not rhyme with *pays*.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The highly irregular verb *to be* is the only verb with more agreement than this in the present tense.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In English, defective verbs generally show no agreement for person or number, they include the modal verbs: *can*, *may*, *shall*, *will*, *must*, *should*, *ought*.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Early Modern English agreement existed for the second person singular of all verbs in the present tense, as well as in the past tense of some common verbs.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] This was usually in the form *-est*, but *-st* and *-t* also occurred.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] This does not affect the endings for other persons and numbers.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Example present tense forms: *thou wilt*, *thou shalt*, *thou art*, *thou hast*, *thou canst*.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Note also the agreement shown by *to be* even in the subjunctive mood.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] However, for nearly all regular verbs, a separate *thou* form was no longer commonly used in the past tense.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Thus the auxiliary verb *to do* is used, e.g.*thou didst help*, not **thou helpedst*.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Indefinite pronouns like *one*, *all*, *everyone*, *everything*, *everybody*, *nothing*, *nobody*, *anyone*, *anything*, *anybody*, *another*, etc. are treated as singular (at least in formal written English).
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Exceptions: *None* is construed in the singular or plural as the sense may require, though the plural is commonly used.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] When *none* is clearly intended to mean *not one*, it should be followed by a singular verb.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The SAT testing service, however, considers *none* to be strictly singular.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The pronouns *neither* and *either* are singular although they seem to be referring to two things.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Words after *each*, *every*, and *many a* are treated as singular.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Exceptions: When the subject is followed by *each*, the verb agrees to the original subject.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] A measurement or quantity is treated as singular.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Exception: "Ten dollars were scattered on the floor" (meaning ten dollar bills).
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Exception: A fraction or percentage can be singular or plural based on the noun that follows it.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] A question with *who* or *what* takes a singular verb.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] A mathematical expression is treated as singular.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Two or more subjects joined by *and* take a plural verb.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Exceptions: If the nouns, however, suggest one idea or refer to the same thing or person, the verb is singular.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Exceptions: Words joined to a subject by *with*, *in addition to*, *along with*, *as well (as)*, *together with*, *besides*, *not*, etc. are parenthetical and the verb agrees with the original subject.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] A quantity expressing a certain number of items (e.g., *dozen*, *score*) is plural.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] A phrase of the form *the* + adjective is plural.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Some words appear singular but are plural: *police*, *cattle*, etc.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] When the word *enemy* is used in the sense of 'armed forces of another nation' a plural verb is used.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] When subjects are joined by *or*, *nor*, *not only ... but also*, etc. the verb agrees with the nearer subject.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] A collective noun is singular when thought of as a unit and plural when the individuals are considered.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Exceptions: British English, however, tends to treat team and company names as plural.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Phrases like *more than one*, *majority of* are singular or plural based on the noun it modifies.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Compared with English, Latin is an example of a highly inflected language.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Verbs must agree in person and number, and sometimes in gender, with their subjects.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Determiners and adjectives must agree in case, number and gender with the nouns they modify.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Latin, a pronoun such as *ego* and *tu* is only inserted for contrast and selection.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Proper nouns and common nouns functioning as subject are nonetheless frequent.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] For this reason, Latin is described as a null-subject language.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Spoken French always distinguishes the second person plural, and the first person plural in formal speech, from each other and from the rest of the present tense in all verbs in the first conjugation (infinitives in *-er*) other than *aller*.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The first person plural form and pronoun (*nous*) are now usually replaced by the pronoun *on* (lit.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] 'one') and a third person singular verb form in Modern French.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Thus, *nous travaillons* (formal) becomes *on travaille*.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In most verbs from the other conjugations, each person in the plural can be distinguished among themselves and from the singular forms, again, when using the traditional first person plural.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The other endings that appear in written French (i.e.: all singular endings, and also the third person plural of verbs other than those with infinitives in *-er*) are often pronounced the same, except in liaison contexts.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Irregular verbs such as *être*, *faire*, *aller*, and *avoir* possess more distinctly pronounced agreement forms than regular verbs.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The final S or T is silent, and the other three forms sound different from one another and from the singular forms.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Adjectives agree in gender and number with the nouns that they modify in French.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] As with verbs, the agreements are sometimes only shown in spelling since forms that are written with different agreement suffixes are sometimes pronounced the same (e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] *joli*, *jolie*); although in many cases the final consonant is pronounced in feminine forms, but silent in masculine forms (e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Most plural forms end in *-s*, but this consonant is only pronounced in liaison contexts, and it is determinants that help understand if the singular or plural is meant.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The participles of verbs agree in gender and number with the subject or object in some instances.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Articles, possessives and other determinants also decline for number and (only in the singular) for gender, with plural determinants being the same for both genders.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Notice that some of the above also change (in the singular) if the following word begins with a vowel: *le* and *la* become *l'*, *du* and *de la* become *de l'*, *ma* becomes *mon* (as if the noun were masculine) and *ce* becomes *cet*.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Hungarian, verbs have polypersonal agreement, which means they agree with more than one of the verb's arguments: not only its subject but also its (accusative) object.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Difference is made between the case when there is a definite object and the case when the object is indefinite or there is no object at all.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Of course, nouns or pronouns may specify the exact object.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In short, there is agreement between a verb and the person and number of its subject and the specificity of its object (which often refers to the person more or less exactly).
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The predicate agrees in number with the subject and if it is copulative (i.e., it consists of a noun/adjective and a linking verb), both parts agree in number with the subject.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] For example: *A könyv**ek** érdekes**ek** volt**ak*** 'The books were interesting' (*a* 'the', *könyv* 'book', *érdekes* 'interesting', *voltak* 'were'): the plural is marked on the subject as well as both the adjectival and the copulative part of the predicate.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Within noun phrases, adjectives do not show agreement with the noun, though pronouns do. e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] *a szép könyv**eitekkel*** 'with your nice books' (*szép* 'nice'): the suffixes of the plural, the possessive 'your' and the case marking 'with' are only marked on the noun.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In the Scandinavian languages, adjectives (both attributive and predicative) are declined according to the gender, number, and definiteness of the noun they modify.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Icelandic and Faroese, adjectives are also declined according to grammatical case, unlike the other Scandinavian languages.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In some cases in Swedish, Norwegian and Danish, adjectives and participles as predicates appear to disagree with their subjects.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] This phenomenon is referred to as pancake sentences.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Norwegian nynorsk, Swedish, Icelandic and Faroese the past participle must agree in gender, number and definiteness when the participle is in an attributive or predicative position.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Icelandic and Faroese, past participles would also have to agree in grammatical case.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In Norwegian bokmål and Danish, past participles are only required to be declined in number and definiteness when in an attributive position.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Most Slavic languages are highly inflected, except for Bulgarian and Macedonian.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The agreement is similar to Latin, for instance between adjectives and nouns in gender, number, case and animacy (if counted as a separate category).
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Verbs have six different forms in the present tense, for three persons in singular and plural.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] As in Latin, the subject is frequently dropped.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Swahili, like all other Bantu languages, has numerous noun classes.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Verbs must agree in class with their subjects and objects, and adjectives with the nouns that they qualify.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] For example: ***Ki**tabu **ki**moja **ki**tatosha* 'One book will be enough)', ***M**chungwa **m**moja **u**tatosha* 'One orange-tree will be enough', *Chungwa moja **li**tatosha* 'One orange will be enough'.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] For example: ***Vi**tabu **vi**wili **vi**tatosha* 'Two books will be enough', ***Mi**chungwa **mi**wili **i**tatosha* 'Two orange-trees will be enough', ***Ma**chungwa **ma**wili **ya**tatosha* 'Two oranges will be enough'.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Class and number are indicated with prefixes (or sometimes their absence), which are not always the same for nouns, adjectives and verbs, as illustrated by the examples.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Many sign languages have developed verb agreement with person.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] The American Sign Language (ASL) verb for 'see' (V handshape), moves from the subject to the object.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In the case of a third-person subject, it goes from a location indexed to the subject to the object, and vice versa.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] Also, in German Sign Language not all verbs are capable of subject/object verb agreement, so an auxiliary verb is used to convey this, carrying the meaning of the previous verb while still inflecting for person.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In addition, some verbs also agree with the classifier the subject takes.
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] In the ASL verb for 'to be under', the classifier a verb takes goes under a downward-facing B handshape (palm facing downward).
[src:argument-linguistics/agreement-linguistics] For example, if a person or an animal was crawled under something, a V handshape with bent fingers would go under the palm, but if it was a pencil, a 1-handshape (pointer finger out) would go under the palm.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Concepts of animacy constantly vary beyond a simple animate and inanimate binary; many languages function off an hierarchical general animacy scale that ranks animacy as a "matter of gradience".
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Typically (with some variation of order and of where the cutoff for animacy occurs), the scale ranks humans above animals, then plants, natural forces, concrete objects, and abstract objects, in that order.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] In referring to humans, this scale contains a hierarchy of persons, ranking the first- and second-person pronouns above the third person, partly a product of empathy, involving the speaker and interlocutor.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] It is obvious that the ability to distinguish between animate and inanimate is very important from an evolutionary point of view.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] In order to survive, an animal must be able to quickly and accurately distinguish between its sexual partners, rivals, predators, animals that it eats, etc., and inanimate objects.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] As for people, the ability to distinguish between animate and inanimate arises in infancy, even before children have mastered speech.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Apparently, there is a brain mechanism responsible for this process.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] De Swart and de Hoop (2018) emphasize the importance of distinguishing between three types of animacy: biological, conceptual, and grammatical.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Each of these types plays a unique role in understanding how humans perceive and express the distinction between animate and inanimate entities.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Biological animacy refers to entities that are biologically alive and is defined by physical properties like the capacity to die.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Conceptual animacy is based on the speaker's perception and cultural background.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] It concerns what is perceived as alive, influenced by the "ego's" perspective and societal beliefs.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] This type often diverges from biological animacy.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] For example, in some cultures or languages, inanimate objects like the sun or mountains are considered "animate" due to mythology or cultural beliefs.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Another example is the term *bot*, which is animate in many languages due to human-like behavior of a bot.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Conceptual animacy reflects how humans personify or attribute agency to non-living entities.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Grammatical animacy demonstrates how biological and conceptual animacy are represented in the grammar of languages.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] It operates as a semantic feature or condition influencing linguistic structures, such as verb agreement or case marking.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] For instance, in Russian, animacy distinctions affect object marking in sentences; animate nouns, such as humans and animals, are treated differently than inanimate nouns.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] This type of animacy illustrates the interaction between cognitive perceptions and linguistic systems.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The animacy hierarchy (e.g., human > animal > inanimate) is widely applied in linguistic analysis to explain various phenomena.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Animate entities are more likely to act as agents or subjects in sentences (agentivity), receive distinct grammatical treatment in case marking or agreement, and be referenced explicitly in discourse.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Additionally, animacy hierarchies are not static; cultural factors or temporary discourse contexts can shift these classifications.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Although animacy distinctions appear universally across languages, their specific implementation varies.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] For example, Navajo uses animacy to govern verb marking, while Slavic languages reflect animacy distinctions in noun declensions.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] However, the universality of animacy as a linguistic feature is debated due to its variability across languages.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Cultural and functional factors can lead to unique animacy hierarchies, showing that animacy is both a universal and context-dependent concept.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The distinction between *he*, *she*, and other personal pronouns, on one hand, and *it*, on the other hand is a distinction in animacy in English and in many Indo-European languages.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The same can be said about distinction between *who* and *what*.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Some languages, such as Turkish, Georgian, spoken Finnish and Italian, do not distinguish between *s/he* and *it*.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] In Finnish, there is a distinction in animacy between *hän*, "he/she", and *se*, "it", but in spoken Finnish **se** can mean "he/she".
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] English shows a similar lack of distinction between *they* animate and *they* inanimate in the plural.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] There is another example of how animacy plays some role in English.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Examples of languages in which an animacy hierarchy is important include the Totonac language in Mexico and the Southern Athabaskan languages (such as Western Apache and Navajo) whose animacy hierarchy has been the subject of intense study.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The Tamil language has a noun classification based on animacy.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The distinction was preserved in Anatolian languages like Hittite, all of which are now extinct.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The animate gender would then later, after the separation of the Anatolian languages, have developed into the feminine and masculine genders.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The plural of neuter/inanimate nouns is believed to have had the same ending as collective nouns in the singular, and some words with the collective noun ending in singular were later to become words with the feminine gender.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Traces can be found in Ancient Greek in which the singular form of verbs was used when they referred to neuter words in plural.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] In many Indo-European languages, such as Latin and the Slavic languages, the plural ending of many neuter words in the merged nominative–accusative–vocative corresponds to the feminine singular nominative form.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Like most other Athabaskan languages, Southern Athabaskan languages show various levels of animacy in their grammar, with certain nouns taking specific verb forms according to their rank in this animacy hierarchy.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Generally, the most animate noun in a sentence must occur first while the noun with lesser animacy occurs second.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] If both nouns are equal in animacy, either noun can occur in the first position.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The *yi-* prefix on the verb indicates that the first noun is the subject and *bi-* indicates that the second noun is the subject.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] There is evidence suggesting that the word order itself is not the important factor.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Instead, the verb construction usually interpreted as the passive voice (e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] "the girl was pecked by the bird") instead indicates that the more animate noun allowed the less animate noun to perform the action (e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] "the girl let herself be pecked by the bird").
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The idea is that things ranked higher in animacy are presumed to be in control of the situation, and that the less-animate thing can only act if the more-animate thing permits it.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Although nouns in Japanese are not marked for animacy, it has two existential/possessive verbs; one for implicitly animate nouns (usually humans and animals) and one for implicitly inanimate nouns (often non-living objects and plants).
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The verb *iru* (いる, also written 居る) is used to show the existence or possession of an animate noun.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The verb *aru* (ある, sometimes written 在る when existential or 有る when possessive) is used to show the existence or possession of an inanimate noun.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] An animate noun, here 'cat', is marked as the subject of the verb with the subject particle *ga* (が), but no topic or location is marked.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] That implies the noun is indefinite and merely exists.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] In the second example, a topic is introduced, in this case "I", with the topic particle *wa* (は).
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The animate noun is again marked with a subject particle, and no location is denoted.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] That implies that the topic owns or is holding onto the noun.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] In the third example, the noun is marked as the topic (and by default functions as the subject of the verb) while a location, here the top of a chair, is marked with the location particle *ni* (に).
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] That implies that the noun is a definite noun and is at the specified location.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] In all these cases, if the noun is not animate, such as a stone, instead of a cat, the verb *iru* must be replaced with the verb *aru* (ある or 有る [possessive] / 在る [existential, locative]).
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] 'There is a robot' (emphasis on its human-like behavior).
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] 'There is a robot' (emphasis on its status as a nonliving thing).
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The Ryukyuan languages, spoken in the Ryukyu Islands, agree in animacy in their case systems.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Middle Korean has genitive particles that were used differently depends on a noun's animacy.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] For an inanimate noun, the particle "-ㅅ" (-s) was used as the inanimate noun's genitive.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Slavic languages that have case (all of them except Bulgarian and Macedonian) have a somewhat complex hierarchy of animacy in which syntactically animate nouns may include both animate and inanimate objects (like mushrooms and dances).
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Overall, the border between animate and inanimate places humans and animals in the former and plants, etc., in the latter, thus basing itself more so on sentience than life.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Animacy functions as a subgender through which noun cases intersect in a phenomenon called syncretism, which here can be either nominative-accusative or genitive-accusative.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Inanimate nouns have accusative forms that take on the same forms as their nominative, with animate nouns marked by having their accusative forms resemble the genitive.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] That syncretism also occurs when restricted by declension class, resulting in syncretism in multiple pronominal forms, such as the Russian reflexive pronoun себя (*sebja*), personal pronouns, and the indefinite interrogative and relative pronoun *kto*.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Elsewhere, animacy is displayed syntactically, such as in endings of modifiers for masc nouns of the second declension.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] While animacy is viewed as primarily semantic when approached diachronically, a synchronic view suggests animacy as a sublevel of gender.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Syntactic gender is defined through patterns in agreement, not necessarily semantic value.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] For example, Russian has "common gender" nouns that refer to traditionally masculine roles but act as syntactically feminine.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Animacy occurs as a subgender of nouns and modifiers (and pronouns only when adjectival) and is primarily reflected in modifier-head agreement (as opposed to subject-predicate agreement).
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Some consider the system to be based on marking inanimacy in which case the gen-acc distinguishes a "non-inanimate" subgender of nouns and modifiers, and others claim that ultimately it is indeed animacy that is marked.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The usage is standard and is found around the Spanish-speaking world.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Spanish personal pronouns are generally omitted if the subject of the sentence is obvious, but when they are explicitly stated, they are used only with people or humanized animals or things.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The inanimate subject pronoun in Spanish is *ello*, like *it* in English (except "ello" can only be used to refer to verbs and clauses, not objects, as all nouns are either masculine or feminine and are referred to with the appropriate pronouns).
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Spanish direct-object pronouns (*me, te, lo, la, se, nos, os, los, las*) do not differentiate between animate and inanimate entities, and only the third persons have a gender distinction.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Thus, for example, the third-person singular feminine pronoun, *la*, could refer to a woman, an animal (like *mariposa*, butterfly), or an object (like *casa*, house), if their genders are feminine.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] In certain dialects, there is a tendency to use *le* (which is usually an indirect object pronoun, meaning "to him/her") as a direct-object pronoun, at the expense of the direct-object pronouns *lo/la*, if the referent is animate.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] That tendency is especially strong if (a) the pronoun is being used as a special second-person pronoun of respect, (b) the referent is male, (c) certain verbs are used, (d) the subject of the verb happens to be inanimate.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] In Classical and Modern Standard Arabic and some other varieties of Arabic, animacy has a limited application in the agreement of plural and dual nouns with verbs and adjectives.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Verbs follow nouns in plural agreement only when the verb comes after the subject.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] When a verb comes before an explicit subject, the verb is always singular.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Also, only animate plural and dual nouns take plural agreement; inanimate plural nouns are always analyzed as singular feminine or plural feminine for the purpose of agreement.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Thus, Arabic المهندسون يطيرون إلى ألمانيا (*Al-muhandisūn yaṭīrūn 'ilā 'Almāniyā*, "The engineers fly to Germany") is masculine plural agreement, but الطائرات تطير إلى ألمانيا (*Al-ṭā'irāt taṭīr 'ilā 'Almāniyā*, "The planes fly to Germany") is feminine singular.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] In general, Arabic divides animacy between عاقل (thinking, or rational) and غير عاقل (unthinking, or irrational).
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Animals fall in the latter category, but their status may change depending on the usage, especially with personification.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Animacy can also condition the nature of the morphologies of split-ergative languages.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] In such languages, participants more animate are more likely to be the agent of the verb, and therefore are marked in an accusative pattern: unmarked in the agent role and marked in the patient or oblique role.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Likewise, less animate participants are inherently more patient-like, and take ergative marking: unmarked when in the patient role and marked when in the agent role.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] In a direct–inverse language, clauses with transitive verbs can be expressed with either a direct or an inverse construction.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The direct construction is used when the subject of the transitive clause outranks the object in salience or animacy.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] The inverse construction is used when the "notional object" outranks the "notional subject".
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] A noun essentially requires the traits of animacy in order to receive the role of Actor and Experiencer.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Additionally, the Agent role is generally assigned to the NP with highest ranking in the animacy hierarchy – ultimately, only animate beings can function as true agents.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Similarly, languages universally tend to place animate nouns earlier in the sentence than inanimate nouns.
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Animacy is a key component of agency – combined with other factors like "awareness of action".
[src:argument-linguistics/animacy] Agency and animacy are intrinsically linked – with each as a "conceptual property" of the other.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] The **antipassive voice** (abbreviated **antip** or **ap**) is a type of grammatical voice that either does not include the object or includes the object in an oblique case.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] The antipassive voice is found in Basque, in Mayan, Salishan, Northeast Caucasian, Austronesian, and Australian languages, and also in some Amazonian languages (e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] Antipassive voice predominantly occurs in ergative languages where the deletion of an object "promotes" the subject from ergative case to absolutive case.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] In certain accusative languages that have verbal agreement with both subject and object, the antipassive is usually formed by deletion of the object affix.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] Examples of accusative languages with this type of antipassive are Maasai, Comanche and Cahuilla.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] A number of direct–inverse languages also have the antipassive voice.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] Somewhat less conventionally, markers that reduce a verb's transitivity by syntactically eliminating objects or demoting them to oblique arguments in accusative languages such as Swedish, Russian or some Turkic languages have recently been described by many linguists as antipassive as well.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] The antipassive voice is very rare in active–stative languages generally and in nominative–accusative languages that have only one-place or no verbal agreement.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] There are a few exceptions to this trend, such as Krongo and the Songhay language Koyraboro Senni, both of which rely on dedicated antipassive markers that are rare in the more typical type of language with an antipassive.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] In the Mayan language Kʼicheʼ, the core arguments of a clause are unmarked for case, and are cross-referenced by person markers on the verb.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] Person marking follows an ergative–absolutive pattern.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] Non-core participants are expressed by prepositional phrases.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] In the following transitive clause, the object "your mother" is the absolutive argument.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] It is unmarked for case and is not overtly cross-referenced, since the absolutive third person singular prefix is zero.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] The agent "you" is represented by the ergative second person singular prefix *a-*.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] In the corresponding antipassive clause, which is formally intransitive, the verb takes the antipassive suffix *-on*.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] The original object "your mother" is now expressed by a prepositional phrase, while the agent "you" has become the subject argument and is thus expressed by the absolutive second person singular prefix *at-*.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] Basque has an antipassive voice which puts the agent into the absolutive case but does not delete the absolutive object.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] This leads to the agent and object being in the same case.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] A further purpose of antipassive construction is often to make certain arguments available as pivots for relativization, coordination of sentences, or similar constructions.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] For example, in Dyirbal the omitted argument in conjoined sentences must be in absolutive case.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] In the conjoined sentence, the omitted argument (the man) would have to be in ergative case, being the agent of a transitive verb (to see).
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] In addition, antipassives frequently convey aspectual, modal and temporal information.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] They are preferred in imperfective, inceptive, potential, purposive and non-past-tense clauses and may hence signal that the clause belongs to these types.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] This is connected to the antipassives' general focus on the agent, which makes them frequent in clauses where the agent is in control of the action or the action depends on the proneness of the agent to perform it.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] The term *antipassive* is applied to a wide range of grammatical structures and is therefore difficult to define.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] The object takes a peripheral role in the clause, getting marked by a non-core case/preposition/etc.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] This can be omitted, but there's always the option of including it.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] There is some explicit marking of the construction.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] While the first, second and fourth criterion are widely accepted, Dixon's formulation of the third criterion is controversial, in that many linguists consider as antipassives also constructions that give *no* option of including the object.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] The antipassive construction is often signalled by the same markers as the reflexive and reciprocal constructions, the unifying feature being a reduction in transitivity.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] Indeed, it is more common for languages to have a coincidence of the antipassive marker with other markers than to have a specialised antipassive marker.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] Other attested origins are from benefactive/malefactive constructions and indefinite/generic object markers.
[src:argument-linguistics/antipassive-voice] For Godoberi, it has been argued that rather than the antipassive having the secondary function of signalling atelic aspect, it has itself arisen as a side-effect of an atelic aspect marker.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] In linguistics, an **argument** is an expression that helps complete the meaning of a predicate, the latter referring in this context to a main verb and its auxiliaries.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] In this regard, the *complement* is a closely related concept.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Most predicates take one, two, or three arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] A predicate and its arguments form a *predicate–argument structure*.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The discussion of predicates and arguments is associated most with (content) verbs and noun phrases (NPs), although other syntactic categories can also be construed as predicates and as arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Arguments must be distinguished from adjuncts.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] While a predicate needs its arguments to complete its meaning, the adjuncts that appear with a predicate are optional; they are not necessary to complete the meaning of the predicate.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Most theories of syntax and semantics acknowledge arguments and adjuncts, although the terminology varies, and the distinction is generally believed to exist in all languages.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Dependency grammars sometimes call arguments *actants*, following Lucien Tesnière (1959).
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Predicates have a valence; they determine the number and type of arguments that can or must appear in their environment.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The valence of predicates is also investigated in terms of subcategorization.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The basic analysis of the syntax and semantics of clauses relies heavily on the distinction between arguments and adjuncts.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The clause predicate, which is often a content verb, demands certain arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] That is, the arguments are necessary in order to complete the meaning of the verb.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The adjuncts that appear, in contrast, are not necessary in this sense.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The subject phrase and object phrase are the two most frequently occurring arguments of verbal predicates.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Each of these sentences contains two arguments (in bold), the first noun (phrase) being the subject argument, and the second the object argument.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] *Jill*, for example, is the subject argument of the predicate *likes*, and *Jack* is its object argument.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Verbal predicates that demand just a subject argument (e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] *sleep*, *work*, *relax*) are intransitive, verbal predicates that demand an object argument as well (e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] *like*, *fry*, *help*) are transitive, and verbal predicates that demand two object arguments are ditransitive (e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] When additional information is added to our three example sentences, one is dealing with adjuncts, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The added phrases (in bold) are adjuncts; they provide additional information that is not necessary to complete the meaning of the predicate *likes*.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] One key difference between arguments and adjuncts is that the appearance of a given argument is often obligatory, whereas adjuncts appear optionally.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] While typical verb arguments are subject or object nouns or noun phrases as in the examples above, they can also be prepositional phrases (PPs) (or even other categories).
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Subject and object arguments are known as *core arguments*; core arguments can be suppressed, added, or exchanged in different ways, using voice operations like passivization, antipassivization, applicativization, incorporation, etc.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Prepositional arguments, which are also called *oblique arguments*, however, do not tend to undergo the same processes.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Psycholinguistic theories must explain how syntactic representations are built incrementally during sentence comprehension.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Argument status determines the cognitive mechanism in which a phrase will be attached to the developing syntactic representations of a sentence.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Psycholinguistic evidence supports a formal distinction between arguments and adjuncts, for any questions about the argument status of a phrase are, in effect, questions about learned mental representations of the lexical heads.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] An important distinction acknowledges both syntactic and semantic arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Content verbs determine the number and type of syntactic arguments that can or must appear in their environment; they impose specific syntactic functions (e.g. subject, object, oblique, specific preposition, possessor, etc.) onto their arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] These syntactic functions will vary as the form of the predicate varies (e.g. active verb, passive participle, gerund, nominal, etc.).
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] In languages that have morphological case, the arguments of a predicate must appear with the correct case markings (e.g. nominative, accusative, dative, genitive, etc.) imposed on them by their predicate.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The semantic arguments of the predicate, in contrast, remain consistent, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The predicate 'like' appears in various forms in these examples, which means that the syntactic functions of the arguments associated with *Jack* and *Jill* vary.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The object of the active sentence, for instance, becomes the subject of the passive sentence.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Despite this variation in syntactic functions, the arguments remain semantically consistent.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] In each case, *Jill* is the experiencer (= the one doing the liking) and *Jack* is the one being experienced (= the one being liked).
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] In other words, the syntactic arguments are subject to syntactic variation in terms of syntactic functions, whereas the thematic roles of the arguments of the given predicate remain consistent as the form of that predicate changes.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The syntactic arguments of a given verb can also vary across languages.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] For example, the verb *put* in English requires three syntactic arguments: subject, object, locative (e. g.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] These syntactic arguments correspond to the three semantic arguments agent, theme, and goal.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The Japanese verb *oku* 'put', in contrast, has the same three semantic arguments, but the syntactic arguments differ, since Japanese does not require three syntactic arguments, so it is correct to say *Kare ga hon o oita* ("He put the book").
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The equivalent sentence in English is ungrammatical without the required locative argument, as the examples involving *put* above demonstrate.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] For this reason, a slight paraphrase is required to render the nearest grammatical equivalent in English: *He positioned the book* or *He deposited the book*.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] A large body of literature has been devoted to distinguishing arguments from adjuncts.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Numerous syntactic tests have been devised for this purpose.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] One such test is the relative clause diagnostic.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] If the test constituent can appear after the combination *which occurred/happened* in a relative clause, it is an adjunct, not an argument, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The same diagnostic results in unacceptable relative clauses (and sentences) when the test constituent is an argument, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The utility of the relative clause test is, however, limited.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] It incorrectly suggests, for instance, that modal adverbs (e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] *probably*, *certainly*, *maybe*) and manner expressions (e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] *quickly*, *carefully*, *totally*) are arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] If a constituent passes the relative clause test, however, one can be sure that it is *not* an argument.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] A further division blurs the line between arguments and adjuncts.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Many arguments behave like adjuncts with respect to another diagnostic, the omission diagnostic.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Adjuncts can always be omitted from the phrase, clause, or sentence in which they appear without rendering the resulting expression unacceptable.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Some arguments (obligatory ones), in contrast, cannot be omitted.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] There are many other arguments, however, that are identified as arguments by the relative clause diagnostic but that can nevertheless be omitted, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The relative clause diagnostic would identify the constituents in bold as arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The omission diagnostic here, however, demonstrates that they are not obligatory arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The insight, then, is that a three-way division is needed.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] On the one hand, one distinguishes between arguments and adjuncts, and on the other hand, one allows for a further division between obligatory and optional arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Most work on the distinction between arguments and adjuncts has been conducted at the clause level and has focused on arguments and adjuncts to verbal predicates.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The distinction is crucial for the analysis of noun phrases as well, however.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] If it is altered somewhat, the relative clause diagnostic can also be used to distinguish arguments from adjuncts in noun phrases, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The diagnostic identifies *Bill's* and *of the poem* as arguments, and *bold* and *after lunch* as adjuncts.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The distinction between arguments and adjuncts is often indicated in the tree structures used to represent syntactic structure.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] In phrase structure grammars, an adjunct is "adjoined" to a projection of its head predicate in such a manner that distinguishes it from the arguments of that predicate.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The distinction is quite visible in theories that employ the X-bar schema, e.g.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The complement argument appears as a sister of the head X, and the specifier argument appears as a daughter of XP.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The optional adjuncts appear in one of a number of positions adjoined to a bar-projection of X or to XP.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Theories of syntax that acknowledge n-ary branching structures and hence construe syntactic structure as being flatter than the layered structures associated with the X-bar schema must employ some other means to distinguish between arguments and adjuncts.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] In this regard, some dependency grammars employ an arrow convention.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Arguments receive a "normal" dependency edge, whereas adjuncts receive an arrow edge.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The arrow edges in the tree identify four constituents (= complete subtrees) as adjuncts: *At one time*, *actually*, *in congress*, and *for fun*.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The normal dependency edges (= non-arrows) identify the other constituents as arguments of their heads.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Thus *Sam*, *a duck*, and *to his representative in congress* are identified as arguments of the verbal predicate *wanted to send*.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Argumentation theory focuses on how logical reasoning leads to end results through an internal structure built of premises, a method of reasoning and a conclusion.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] There are many versions of argumentation that relate to this theory that include: conversational, mathematical, scientific, interpretive, legal, and political.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Grammar theory, specifically functional theories of grammar, relate to the functions of language as the link to fully understanding linguistics by referencing grammar elements to their functions and purposes.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] A variety of theories exist regarding the structure of syntax, including generative grammar, categorial grammar, and dependency grammar.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Modern theories of semantics include formal semantics, lexical semantics, and computational semantics.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Formal semantics focuses on truth conditioning.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Lexical Semantics delves into word meanings in relation to their context and computational semantics uses algorithms and architectures to investigate linguistic meanings.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The concept of valence is the number and type of arguments that are linked to a predicate, in particular to a verb.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] In valence theory verbs' arguments include also the argument expressed by the subject of the verb.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The notion of argument structure was first conceived in the 1980s by researchers working in the government–binding framework to help address controversies about arguments.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The distinction between arguments and adjuncts is crucial to most theories of syntax and grammar.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Arguments behave differently from adjuncts in numerous ways.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] Theories of binding, coordination, discontinuities, ellipsis, etc. must acknowledge and build on the distinction.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] When one examines these areas of syntax, what one finds is that arguments consistently behave differently from adjuncts and that without the distinction, our ability to investigate and understand these phenomena would be seriously hindered.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] There is a distinction between arguments and adjuncts which is not really noticed by many in everyday language.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] The difference is between obligatory phrases versus phrases which embellish a sentence.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] For instance, if someone says "Tim punched the stuffed animal", the phrase stuffed animal would be an argument because it is the main part of the sentence.
[src:argument-linguistics/argument-linguistics] If someone says, "Tim punched the stuffed animal with glee", the phrase with glee would be an adjunct because it just enhances the sentence and the sentence can stand alone without it.
